muggling voyage in vivid detail. Starting from that horrible night in June 1743, it narrates a deeply human history of smuggling, providing an incredible story of those caught in the webs spun by illicit commerce. The case generated a rich documentary record that illuminates an international chocolate smuggling ring, the lives of the crew and mutineers, and the harrowing experience of the enslaved people trafficked by the Rising Sun. Smuggling stood at the center of the lives of everyone involved with the business of the schooner. Larger forces, such as imperial trade restrictions, created the conditions for smuggling, but individual actors, often driven by raw ambition and with little regard for the consequences of their actions, designed, refined, and perpetuated this illicit commerce. At once startling and captivating, Mutiny on the Rising Sun shows how illegal trade created demand for exotic products like chocolate, and how slavery and smuggling were integral to the development of American capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSlaveryzUnited States. 0aSmugglingzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerindians.  aAnglo-Dutch Relations.  aAnomabu.  aBarbados.  aBoston.  aBritish Atlantic.  aChocolate.  aCommerce.  aCriminal Justice.  aEarly America.  aGold Coast.  aInsurance.  aMemory.  aMerchants.  aMolasses Act.  aMutiny.  aNavigation Acts.  aNew England.  aNewark Jackson.  aOld North Church.  aPlantations.  aRace.  aSailors.  aSlave Trade.  aSlavery.  aSmuggling.  aSuriname.  aWar of Jenkin’s Ear.  aWest Indies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLE